	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

Culture is important in any negotiation. Culture can be known by what it is not and by what it is. It is not the same everywhere. It is not one thing. It is not just one way. Saying “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating” is too simple. Knowing general ideas about a culture is good. But it is better for a negotiator to know how culture affects talks. When you meet a foreign culture, you see it through your own culture and compare them.

To understand a culture, you can study its history or know its likes and dislikes. Do not judge or try to change a culture. Accept it and work within it, especially if you are in a weaker position. If you are in a foreign place, respect local ways. This helps to overcome cultural barriers and move talks forward.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies also have their own culture. A company might want long work hours or a relaxed schedule. You see company culture in how people dress, talk, and work. Some companies support all charity work, others only support certain ones. American companies show different cultures from place to place. Some cultures may look the same from the outside, but they have their own differences.

Values are important to know because they show why a culture acts a certain way. If a culture values saving face or harmony, a negotiator will not shame others to win. A culture that likes hard bargaining will not settle quickly. Think about these before talks. But it is also good to know the person you negotiate with to make talks work well.

The fool says in his heart, "There is no God." This line comes from Psalm 14 in the Christian Bible. It starts St. Anselm's argument about the existence of God. This belief is also held by another person, Thomas Aquinas, whom we will talk about. Both argue that God exists, and we want to see which argument is better. So, we will assume they both believe in the God of the Bible. If we think about a different kind of god, we cannot compare their arguments well. They both talk about one idea of God. Even though both make good points, neither gives a complete reason to believe in God.

First, we will look at St. Anselm's argument. Anselm says we understand God through faith. We look inside ourselves to find proof of God. He says that because we understand God, we cannot think of God as not existing. This idea can be hard to understand, but it means proof of God is in our mind. Anselm says we do not need outside evidence to know God is real. This is often called faith in Christian writings.

This idea is not like the one held by Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas says we can prove God exists using reason and evidence, without needing faith. This can help in spreading Christianity because it means new people can be convinced by logic, not just faith. Aquinas talks about five logical reasons for God: change, cause, chance, degrees of goodness, and order. He shows that proof of God comes from logic. If you know a puzzle has a missing piece, you can figure out what it looks like without seeing it.

Writers use different ways to make readers feel or think a certain way about important things. Some ways work better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these ways in his book The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald uses an adjective and a noun together that do not usually go together to create a special feeling around a subject. Other times, he gives meaning to a symbol and uses it for this purpose. Fitzgerald does this with many colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald gives meaning to colors like white/gray and red/pink and uses them to remind readers of a feeling about something important.

The meaning Fitzgerald gives to white/gray is uniformity. White is nicer and higher class, while gray is older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning at the start of the book by using these colors often. Daisy and Jordan are often “in white”—in fact, everyone wears white: Nick wears “white flannels” to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears a “white shirt” when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white.” The only time people are not wearing white is when Nick sees Gatsby’s party: “the halls... are gaudy with primary colors.” Fitzgerald also uses these colors to describe common things: Nick goes to work “down the white chasms of lower New York,” names of people at Gatsby’s parties are “gray names” on Nick’s list, and Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—uniformity. Common places or people are also white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a “white girlhood” together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” in the valley of ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray,” and the dog-seller is “a gray old man.”

Once Fitzgerald gives enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to show unimportance or uniformity. This starts with Daisy. After some time without any big use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character, more like something Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald uses more of this around Daisy to show her as a uniform addition, like the “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar,” and she is again in a “white” dress before Tom and Gatsby’s meeting.

San Diego County has good farming because of its mild, sunny weather. Common plants grown here are tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a large market for organic food from local farms in San Diego. Many groups have long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also liked. Many organic farms offer tours and let people hike, watch birds, and do other fun activities. This helps the landowner get government help while making the land better. It also lets them offer farm tours and other ways to make money or teach people.

Organic farming can make more kinds of plants and animals live in the area because it does not use chemicals. But it can cost more than regular farming. It needs more work to keep pests and weeds away and to make the soil rich without chemicals. Losses can be higher, and small farms do not have the same big farm advantages. Other things that help wildlife, like planting cover crops and removing bad plants, also need more work. So, a landowner might look for money or help to make both good profits and good habitats.

The land for this example is next to the town of Potrero in San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. It is in the East County Southern Foothills area of San Diego's Conservation Plan. The plan is being reviewed now and includes over a hundred types of plants and animals. Many are endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, some butterflies, and the California gnatcatcher. Some, like burrowing owls, may soon be endangered, too.

Native Americans lived here for many centuries. In the late 1800s, cattle ranchers and wood sellers settled here. This land was part of an old homestead and was likely used for grazing or wood production for many years.

I picked a property from a real estate website. I checked what government programs are available to help a small farmer save costs and keep the farm friendly to wildlife. I found an organic farm nearby as an example of what someone farming this land might try to do.

There is a strong link between brothers. This link cannot be broken. Many feelings are part of this link: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers know each other well. They see themselves when they look at their brother. This link shows its true nature in hard times. It can be good or bad. These feelings have a cost. Understanding these feelings means dealing with what they bring. When a brother looks at another and sees himself, he sees his true self. Actions and their results show true character. In “The Scarlet Ibis,” two brothers explore this. They feel many strong emotions. They travel through a rich land. They go on a journey that cannot succeed. In the end, only one brother lives. The story shows the theme through Doodle, the main character. Their talks and the narrator’s view show complex feelings. These feelings shape actions.

The main character’s actions come from one feeling: pride. From the start, he feels upset with Doodle, his brother. He wanted to teach Doodle many things, like holding his breath, running, jumping, or climbing vines. He wanted a brother to race to Horsehead Landing. He wanted someone to sit with at the top of a big tree. But Doodle cannot do these things. Doodle was born with a weak heart. It was unlikely he would live or do hard physical activities. The young main character had big dreams. These dreams were crushed. He even thought about killing Doodle by putting a pillow over his face. What kind of child would think this? But he changes when Doodle smiles at him. This small act gives him hope. This shows he always had love for his brother deep inside.

The human brain is a complex system that handles information. As technology improved, the ways to describe the brain changed too. At first, people compared the brain to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, later to a book, and now to a computer. When you learn about the brain, remember that these comparisons have limits and can cause wrong ideas.

Information processing begins with input from the senses. The senses change things like touch, heat, sound, or light into signals in the brain. The brain changes this information many times. This happens through bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when you see a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing helps you know simple things like color and shape. It helps you see the box. Top-down processing helps you recognize the box faster. It might help you know it is a black box and not a hole in the white background.

After some processing, an attention filter decides how important the information is. It also decides which processes should use it. For example, when you look at grass, your brain sees each blade. But a good attention filter stops you from noticing each one. Yet, you might hear your name in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and attention affects processing many times.

The brain must store information to process it. There are different kinds of memory, like sensory, working, and long-term memory. First, information is encoded. Each type of sensory input has its own encoding. For example, words can be encoded by how they look, sound, or what they mean. After storing, information must be kept. Some studies in animals show that working memory, which holds information for about 20 seconds, is kept by signals moving in a loop through the brain. Long-term memory might be kept in proteins in the brain.

There are many ideas about how the brain organizes knowledge. Some ideas come from how people remember things, others from computer science, and others from studying the brain. The semantic network model says there are nodes for concepts. These nodes are connected by how related they are. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” and “table” might be linked to “wooden.”

In 2007, the United States fell into a deep financial crisis. Unemployment rose, the housing market crashed, and many big American companies were ruined. This recession is still here, so we must ask: how did this crisis happen, and how can we stop it? The crisis was caused by poor political choices that pushed banks to give risky loans in a weak financial system. At the same time, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were pushed to support and repackage these loans. When people could not pay back their loans, banks had little money left and this caused more problems for the economy.  

The crisis started in 1999 during President Clinton's time. He wanted to be more popular to win another term. To do this, his government made it easier to get loans, which set the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times said in 1999 that Fannie Mae was under pressure to give more loans to people with low and moderate incomes. He warned that this could lead to problems if the economy got worse, needing a government rescue like in the 1980s. As he predicted, bad lending practices led to the economy's meltdown.  

Many things caused the economy to fail, including new and complex mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations were used a lot before the crisis. They connected more parts of the economy to the housing market. This made U.S. households and financial markets take on too much risk in housing, making them vulnerable to even small price changes.  

Indeed, when the housing bubble burst, financial institutions that bought these mortgage-backed securities suffered. The top five U.S. investment banks reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, about 30% of the USA's GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply, Lehman Brothers was closed, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became commercial banks under strict rules. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and came under government control in September 2008.

Exposition is a part of a story where a writer gives information. It can be interesting or it can make readers bored. Some readers do not like too much information. They might stop reading if there is too much.

Exposition is not good.

Many readers know the advice, "Show, don't tell." But some writers still write long parts where nothing happens. Exposition tells you what happened. In movies, one character might tell another a lot of information. In stories, the writer does this.

Here is an example. In a story, you learn that the main character met her loved one at a certain place and time. They got married in a big way, and her husband was killed in front of her. You do not want this to take two pages with little talk. You want to know the husband better. You want to know how he speaks and acts, showing his love for her. You want to see how much she loves him too. This helps you understand her more and feel sad when he dies.

In short, you want more than just "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to give more details. It is easy to skip them. Maybe you have a new character. You know he was in the Air Force. Now, he is a night manager at a gas station. He was married twice, has no kids, likes fishing, wants to own the gas station, and ate Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news shows from Columbus, Ohio. The first was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio. He stabbed his wife. His name is Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture. He looked very bad. They talked about this for two minutes. The story was still developing. They said he stabbed her many times and was arrested. I think this was the right amount of time for the story.

The second story was about a shooting. Travis Buyers, 18, was shot. It happened in the Sharon Woods area. He was hurt badly. No one was arrested. There were no suspects. The SWAT Team was looking into it. This story was short. I think it was because he was a black man or it was a black neighborhood. I notice that minority victims do not get much attention. If a white person is a crime victim, the media covers it a lot. But if it is a minority person, it might not even be mentioned.

The next story was about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. They said where they thought it happened. It was a .22 caliber bullet. Crime-Stoppers offer a five-thousand dollar reward for tips. This could lead to the arrest of the shooter.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon. They said temperatures would be in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The time spent on this was short. They wanted people to keep watching.

They also had a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said a dark-skinned black man robbed the store. He wore a hoodie. He was six feet tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. They spent a lot of time saying he was black and very dark.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug dealer from Texas. He was guilty of bringing large amounts of marijuana to Ohio from Texas. They said he got a 25-year sentence in prison as "300" months. I do not know why they said it that way. Maybe it sounds harsher. They also said he was Hispanic. I do not think this was important to the story.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a kind of security. It follows an index, a commodity, or a group of assets like an index fund. But, it is more flexible and trades like a stock. An ETF gives you the range of an index fund and the benefits of owning a single stock. You can sell short, buy on margin, and purchase as low as one share. Expense ratios of ETFs are lower than average mutual funds. But, you must pay a commission on any trade with ETFs, just like a stock order. There are many types of ETFs. It is wise for an investor to check if the benefits, like range, are real. For this study, we will look at the ETF IHF and compare it with its top 10 stocks. We want to see if one ETF is as good as owning 10 stocks and if there are better ways to hold these stocks for a better return.

For this study, we will focus only on the top ten stocks of the ETF. These stocks make up 63.58% of the ETF's total assets. Below are these top 10 stocks and their percentage of total assets.

We can check how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF by looking at the percent of assets, normalized to 100%. We calculate their contributions to Beta and Return if a portfolio was made of these 10 stocks in the same way as the ETF. The Beta and return calculations are in the chart below.

From the chart, we see that a portfolio with only these ten stocks has a 6.11% higher return than the ETF. That is a 16% increase in returns. The Beta of the top ten stocks is .12 lower than the whole ETF. So far, it looks like a portfolio of just the top 10 stocks could give a higher return with a lower beta. But, these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To check if these portfolios are different, we find the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks. We then normalize it to 100% to compare their combined standard deviation with the ETF IHF.

Looking back at Figure 17, there was a big drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was not encouraging, and it is hard to know why it happened. Winter starts at a New England campus, and fewer people commute by bicycle or foot, which might explain some of the drop. December is the end of the fall semester when everyone is busy finishing schoolwork and grading. So, many might have forgotten to fill out the commuter log. Also, December brings the holiday season and a long break for students and faculty, and many do not need to come to campus. Classes start again in late January, which might explain the low number of logs for that month. But this does not explain the low submissions for February. It is possible that any project like this has excitement at the start, which then fades. To fight this, we made a Carpool Challenge Week in March to bring back energy to the project, which did increase log submissions. One challenge we faced was keeping project energy up despite natural drops in interest and the breaks in the school year. 

Another challenge for this project, or any project about different ways to commute, is that people like the freedom of driving their cars. This is part of our culture. So, it is important to give reasons to try other ways to commute. We gave many prizes like gift cards to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage places, a bookstore, and some big chain stores. It would have been interesting to see how bigger prizes might have changed participation, like giving away a nice bicycle, a hybrid car, or an electric car. This might have helped with the drop in interest. The nature of the prizes did not change during the project. But if the prizes had grown in value over time, that might have helped. The gift cards were enough at first, but if we had announced in December that we were adding some bicycles, and then in January a hybrid or electric car, it is likely that more people would have stayed engaged instead of losing interest.

I looked at early films made by Edison in the Library of Congress. I watched all the trick films from 1895 to 1901. There were fifteen trick films. These films use editing to make illusions. I studied how these films were made and how some later films changed. Most trick films at that time did not move the camera. They used a stage-like setup. They showed long or medium shots. They used one shot to make one film. But some films in the early 1900s used more than one shot.

Most trick films were made in a set that looked like a stage. The camera stayed still. It did not follow people or things. This style came from the theatre and magic shows. Actors in these films mostly moved side to side. They did not move closer to or away from the camera. For example, in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors entered from the right and moved back and forth. Even when they left the frame, the camera did not move.

The stage style meant that trick films used long shots, and sometimes medium shots. They did not use close-up shots. This was like theatre, where people watched the whole stage at once. In early films, actors stayed in the middle, so close-ups did not happen.

Most early trick films used one shot for the whole film. This made most films last a minute or less. They showed short tricks, like magic or disappearing acts, with little story. But one shot in these films was not always one real shot. It might be many shots joined to make an illusion. In The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), you can see where the real shot with Mary’s "head" starts if you look closely. But to the viewer, it looks like one shot.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is a mix of "Old-New," as Ian Watt says in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. People have both criticized and praised the Gothic style. Some say it lacks depth, while others admire its 'terrible sublime' quality (Burke). The first "Gothic Novel," called The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole, mixed old and new story ideas. This created a new type of writing. Walpole used old theater ideas and new ways of showing nature in modern stories to make what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic style includes ideas from old gothic theater, building styles, and traditions. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, "gothic" meant many things. It seemed old or not modern compared to new ideas in society and writing. The mix of the old "Gothic" style and the new novel form, which lets readers see inside characters' minds, keeps Gothic writing alive. It seems both old and new to modern readers.  

One main idea in Gothic novels is Chivalry. In the past, chivalry meant training to be a good knight. This idea stays and changes in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry matters to Gothic writers because it stands for the brave, honorable knight. Writers like Walpole thought society lacked this ideal. By using chivalry, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized. This hints at Gothic turning into Romantic writing. It also tries to make the present better. When Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto, he was in a troubled political time and worried about the future. He was involved in politics and faced unfair accusations. He might have thought the goodness of the gothic era was lost in his time. This idea is clear in his characters, like Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, readers know he has many chivalric traits. He is described as:

Frederic is shown with many traditional knightly images. He is a prince, has suffered, faced tragedy, left, and is thought to have been killed by enemies. The idea of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the Gothic theme of excess (66).

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from customer orders to raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to customers. The term "supply chain management" was created in 1982 by a consultant named Keith Oliver. He explained the process of planning, doing, and controlling what happens in the supply chain to meet customer needs quickly and well. There are six main parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these six parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step in the supply chain. It is the base for the whole process. The production stage shows when, why, where, and how things will be made. Managers need to know what customers want. To know this, managers can look at the market. The market helps decide what customers want. After managers understand what customers want, they decide what products to make and how many. Then, they decide where to make the products and which plant is best for volume and quality. They must keep in mind customer demand and satisfaction. After choosing a production place, managers plan work schedules and equipment care. Production is important in the supply chain. Every detail is important in the process. If not planned well, it can cost the company time and money. For example, I worked at Wal-Mart and Target. Both have plans and processes for each part of the business. There is a plan for how an employee's uniform should look and how to receive shipments from trucks. Having clear processes helps a company work well without confusion.

The second key part of supply chain management is supply. Supply means making big decisions to decide what a facility can do and growing partnerships from these decisions. A company may have many production parts for one product. Each part has different equipment, workers, and skills. The manager must decide which part is best for each product process. Management may also decide to give work to other companies. The main reason to give work to other companies is to create speed. Speed means giving quality and flexibility while keeping costs low.

Victorian novels often have a lot of detail and focus on the rich people of the time. But two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have mystery and strange events, which is not usual for that time. This makes the characters stronger and helps us understand their reasons and feelings better.

In Oliver Twist, strange events happen like dreams. These show what Oliver feels, what hurts him, and what he knows about the truth around him. In chapter 28, Oliver remembers being shot. It feels like a dream, and he tries to find help. This shows how little control he had over what happened. Oliver’s health is bad, and he sees things that are not real, like Sikes and Crackit. The shooting is too much for him. His senses are not working well, and he does not notice the “unseen hand” taking him away. He feels pain and fear, and he wonders whose actions caused his trouble, because it was not his choice. This shows that Oliver cannot control what happens to him. He does not even try to change things when in danger. This suggests that Oliver feels defeated, as if Fagin is breaking him and making him accept despair. If not, he might have tried to save himself.

The day passed. There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came. Night came again; a night so long in its quiet and yet so short in its fast hours.

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program helping young students. I tried to help them in any subject they found hard, but I was best at English and reading. One of the teachers asked me to help a boy named Adrian. I think he was in third or fourth grade. Adrian had many problems with reading. I noticed something strange. He could pronounce some letters well, but others not at all. Adrian was Latino, and he spoke English perfectly. We had trouble until I met his mother. I was watching some children while others were on a field trip when his mother came in. She did not speak English, only Spanish. I spoke a little Spanish, and we talked. Then, I realized Adrian could read, but he did not know the English alphabet well. I am not sure if this helped him much, but I hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story to talk about the language problem in schools, especially in California. It shows that it is not always clear. Even a child who speaks perfect English may find reading hard. We all agree this problem is real, so what can we do? For Adrian, the answer was simple: help with reading English, the alphabet, and pronunciations. For children who speak little English, the answer is harder. There is no one solution. The dual language system, immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes together can help.

First, the dual language system is a good idea. It is not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. Studies show that children in bilingual programs do better in school. Some people fear it is a waste of resources and that most children will not benefit. But that is not true. If we use these programs more, all children will gain from them. How should we do this? Should all teachers be bilingual? No, that is not reasonable. But we can have special aides or tutors who are bilingual.

As children, many of us hear there is something bigger than we are. Some of us go to Sunday school or Temple to learn about it. Others look inside themselves for answers. Many accept the religion of their parents. Some reject it, saying nothing exists beyond what we know. We may change our beliefs over time. Whatever we choose, we try to find a part of ourselves through spirituality. We look for light to guide us out of the dark.

"My favorite bird is a cardinal," my father said. We sat on the porch, listening to the rain on the roof. We smoked cigarettes together. Rainwater filled the gutters and drowned the plants by the porch. My father looked out at the rain, as if searching or remembering. He had lost weight, and his clothes hung loose. His hair was thinner than before. He kept looking at the rain, not at me. I felt alone and scared. I could not tell him how much I would miss him. Talking about it would make it real. I hugged him, sat closer, and looked at the rain with him.

My father died in December, five days after my birthday. The treatment did not ease his pain but kept him alive longer. I did not understand why he had to suffer more. I wondered what kind of God would allow this. Alone at night, I did not pray. If God was real, I thought, He stopped listening to me.

I did not want to see my father die. So, I did not. I wanted to remember him for how he lived. I knew him better than others did. I knew he would not want me to watch him die. I stayed in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early supporter of Republicanism. He worked mainly in farming. His short time in politics made him known for speaking strongly about personal freedom and government. He believed in a farming system and this shaped his ideas about government. He thought farming was the best job. This belief influenced his views on power, the Constitution, and the courts.

John Taylor thought the United States could create a perfect system. There were no old ways to stop new ideas for government. This allowed for self-government. He believed in the natural rights of people. He thought these rights depend on each other. If one right is taken away, all rights suffer. The government should not touch these rights. He said that in nature, strong and clever people gain more. But in society, it should not be like that.

To create a good society, Taylor said a government must consider the good and bad in people. He had strong views on good and bad morals. He said, "As government is run by people, all its good and bad must be human." Good principles protect private property, help farming, and limit capitalism. A government with good principles works fairly even if run by selfish people. Self-interest drives people, but it is bad when it harms others. Good government is needed to control man's bad side and must be watched to avoid bad principles.

Taylor, like other strong Republicans then, wanted to strictly follow the Constitution. He wanted a small Federal government with only the powers clearly given in the Constitution. He knew a big Federal government costs much and could become controlling. But he thought a simple reading of the Constitution was risky. Without knowing the writers' intent, it could become corrupt. He saw the Declaration of Independence as the true guide of the United States because it clearly shows the country as a group of states, not one nation.

I looked down, my mind trying to understand what I saw. I felt no emotion and stayed quiet. My mind studied the view, but it did not connect it to any big ideas. Thoughts came and went quickly. My mind worked so smoothly that it felt like I had no real thoughts, only a clear experience of seeing.

Once, an artist I knew told me to buy an art book. It was called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I wanted to learn to draw since I was six. This book taught many things, like how the brain sees lines. One thing the book taught was to put a square frame around a picture you want to study. This makes a big picture, like a fruit bowl in a kitchen, easier to see as just the bowl on a table.

At that moment, I looked at the bowl in front of me. I could not imagine the artist's frame. I was amazed and could only look in wonder. Artists like Picasso and Monet had their styles. If I wanted to call myself an artist, this was my start, my Work in Brown.

I touched my tool, my hand moved, and my mind's will took form. Water swirled and was clear. Small pieces broke away and were washed away. I tried again, hitting the toilet handle. The brown thing stayed, stuck at the bottom.

I held a mop, feet apart, a green tie around my neck. I frowned at the mess someone left in the Rite Aid bathroom. After a few more flushes and some quiet moments, I reached for the toilet paper. I wrapped my hand like an oven mitt. I stood up, bent down, and slowly reached into the bowl, like a mother reaching for a turkey in the oven.

Teenagers are dying in car crashes. Many things cause this. Young American drivers have the highest death rate. The National Institutes of Health say part of the problem is the teen brain is not ready for driving dangers. Simple lack of experience is also a big problem. This leads to more deadly crashes, more rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.

Teens do worse when they drive with friends. They do this often. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found a link between the age of passengers and the number of crashes.

California and other states try to make teen drivers safer. They have rules for temporary licenses. These rules limit driving hours and do not allow other young people as passengers.

But these rules are not enough, in my opinion. Young drivers, as a group, are not ready for driving risks and duties. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman thinks even 18 is too young for a full driver's license. USA Today says Zuckerman’s research shows young people under 19-20 like to take risks for fun. It makes sense to delay driving until this risk-taking eases. If we keep giving licenses to young teens, we will see more deadly crashes. The number of deaths could get very high soon. By 2010, many teens, children of Baby Boomers, will be ready to drive.

Making laws for this would be simple. Schools can still teach driving classes for future drivers, but no one under 18 could drive a car. A temporary permit could still be given before a full license, and a certain number of driving practice hours would still be needed. The number of hours could be based on what most states require (for example, California needs 6 hours of driving training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Because the deadly crash numbers for teen drivers are from all states, national laws on this issue would be a good way to protect teens across the country.

The laws I suggest are not new ideas.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a short meaning of the disorder. Next, it explains how to find out if someone has it, including common signs. Finally, the paper ends with ways a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is about how well the brain uses hearing information. It means the brain does not process sounds correctly. People with CAPD can hear normally, so they are not considered "hearing impaired." The part of the brain that helps us understand what we hear does not work as it should. This can make it hard to separate words or hear conversations over noise.

The first mention of CAPD was in the 1950s. It was called “auditory imperception” when researchers were studying children with communication problems. An Italian research team began making tests for these children in 1954. In 1961, another researcher introduced new testing to explain how the brain hears different sounds. In 1977, a big meeting helped start more studies on children with CAPD.

CAPD can show in many ways. A person may not know where a sound is coming from. They may have trouble telling different sounds apart. They might not recognize sound patterns or changes in speech. One sound might block another. They might not understand sound clues in a useful way. They may also have trouble knowing the order of sounds they hear.

To find out if someone has CAPD, they must be checked by watching how they listen and perform on hearing tests. These tests can be done by hearing experts, speech experts, psychologists, and others. This might include questions, watching how the person acts with sounds, and how they respond to certain noises. There is no single test that works every time, and the cause of CAPD is not known. Many tests use different sounds at the same time and ask the person to pick out certain ones, like words or numbers. More detailed tests record sounds in the ear and measure how the ear responds.

I want to study social work. I plan to work with the Division of Family and Children Services. I want to help children who are abused or neglected. I also want to support families in trouble. I can bring values like service, respect, and ethics to social work. I want to help others improve relationships and improve myself as well. These values are important to social workers and to me.

I always wanted to help others. But I was not sure what job to choose. In high school and college, I saw many people run away from their problems. Some used bad ways to cope. Because of this, I decided to study Psychology. After I finished college in 2009, I took a break. One summer day, I visited a friend. She introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy. He was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, he called the police. I went to his parents' house to help. I talked to the police and said I had a degree in Psychology. The police asked me to talk to the parents. The parents seemed nervous and made excuses for their son's behavior. After this, I thought about a career in social work to help children in family problems.

Social justice is important in social work. Society says the individual is important. But the idea of the "individual" is old. If society values individuals, why do we try to be like everyone else? I am an individual. I do not like to limit myself. In high school and college, I stood against social injustice. I colored my hair, wore clothes that fit my style, pierced my ears, and joined GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance). I fought against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice and will keep fighting against injustice.

This paper talks about two ways to understand the disorder called insomnia. One way looks at genes and medical health. The other way looks at how the environment, race, and social status affect sleep. The paper reviews studies on insomnia to explain these two ways. It also talks about the good and bad points of the studies.

A sleep problem can be a main sleep problem, a sleep problem caused by another mental issue, or a sleep problem caused by other things. Main sleep problems are called Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Sleep problems from a mental issue are linked to other mental disorders. Other sleep problems can be from health issues or substance use. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified. Primary Insomnia is trouble with sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia is trouble staying awake, both lasting at least a month. Narcolepsy involves sudden sleep and automatic REM. Dyssomnias are about starting and keeping sleep. Parasomnias are sleep problems with unusual behaviors. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep problems from mental issues involve trouble sleeping due to other mental disorders. This review talks about insomnia and some main sleep problems in terms of genes and social factors.

The biological way looks at genes, inherited parts, and physical sleep disorder parts. Neurons in the brain's hypothalamus with orexin help control sleep. A study with mice found that certain receptors on neurons are important for sleep. The GABAA receptor helps sleep when active. If it is stopped, it can reduce anxiety and help sleep. A drug that acts on the GABAB receptor made mice sleep more (Matsuki et al., 2009). This means results from mice can help us understand human sleep. There is a gene and environment link to the GABAB receptor in humans. A problem with this receptor can affect sleep without drugs. The social side of this study shows if the receptor is inherited, it can control sleep. A change in the receptor can cause sleep problems which can hurt school, work, and daily life.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years. For many students, including me, getting around campus is hard. In my first year, I lived in East Halls. It is almost the farthest point east on campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in places like Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially if the weather was bad. I talked to a former student who said that a long time ago, East Halls was far from the rest of the school. There was a lot of empty land around it. Now, that space is filled with sports fields, big new buildings like the new Creamery and health services building, and apartments. As the campus grows, moving from one place to another becomes harder. What is the best way to get around? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But just having bikes is not enough. Students need to ride them, and the campus must be built for bikes.

I talked to a friend who started riding a bike again after a long time. He said he did not know why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said. “For a few years, it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” Riding a bike is good for your body and it is the best way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many students, I now live off campus. It is as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The best choice I made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast. The problem is, Pollock Road is the fastest way to Thomas building from my house, and it is not always easy to travel on, even with a bike. Walking has its benefits too, but I’m too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only choice to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add 30-40 minutes to my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Plus, there is more time spent walking to and from other classes and appointments. That’s more time than I can give.

Aldous Huxley talks about the danger of technology and capitalism in his book Brave New World. The story shows a world where people care more about the group than the individual. They are taught from the start to look for quick happiness. The people are like pieces in a big game, following the rules set by the World Controller. If you look at the book through Marxist ideas, you see Huxley's worries about these systems. Marxist words like homogeny and reification show that Huxley is talking about problems in the economy of his time.

Capitalism is made fun of with the idea of false consciousness from Marxism. This means normal people do not really know how they relate to other classes in terms of money. They only care about their own gain. This happens because the ruling class controls the workers, which is clear in Brave New World. The lower classes, like Delta and Gamma, do not have a real will. They are taught to consume and spend above all else. This is controlled by the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea that one group has power over others, is shown here. The lower classes do not know they are being controlled and support the system of capitalism and consumerism. The upper classes can see this control but do little about it. Characters like Bernard are some of the few who notice. The way these social classes interact shows the problems of capitalism.

In Brave New World, people do not have true relationships. The book does not show deep characters, even the main ones. Maybe Huxley is saying technology and capitalism take away people's free will and expression. Love and strong emotions are missing. Interactions are shallow, like when men talk about women only for their looks and women openly talk about their experiences. Each class is happy with their place in society, showing the effect of capitalism. Their complete obedience in their role reflects Marxist views on the working class, who are falsely made to feel they are better as long as they keep consuming and obeying.

Almost four years ago, I took a class on Islam at CBC. One main topic was if Islam is a hostile religion. I think this question is very important today. After 9/11, I saw media change from seeing Islam as hostile to being very tolerant of it in America. I do not think, back in 2001, we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who has a Muslim background in his family.

The life story of the Prophet is interesting to me. From what I know, the story does not match what I learned about Muhammad. I thought Muhammad made people become Muslims by force. He would take over tribes and make them follow Islam. But the story says Muhammad was like a martyr, misunderstood, and humble. Then, people came to see the truth in his teachings.

There are also many similarities between the works of Jesus and the miracles of Muhammad. The most clear is when Muhammad made enough food for forty men from only mutton and milk. This writing style makes me think the writers wanted Muhammad to be seen as a humble prophet who only lived in truth and miracles. This lessens the life and miracles of Jesus Christ. It feels like they are taking from Jesus to add to Muhammad.

Many stories in the life story seem to try to show proof of people converting to Islam on their own. But many stories are from a third-party view. The author says he heard from someone who heard from someone else. I did not like this because it makes the stories seem less true.

What bothers me most is how they try to show Muhammad as a godly man who was humble and gentle. But history does not fully agree with this view of Muhammad. I wonder if Muslims today know the true history of how Muhammad came to power.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus during his life were soon left behind as Christian ideas changed after he died. If we look at this history in a simple way, we see that Christianity moved away from its start. Today, people notice more and have new ideas. Traditional people still exist and they may not like new ideas, but they might not be strong enough to change everything. Among Christians, people will understand more about history in the future. They will want to see what was added to Christianity over time and what Jesus truly wanted. It may take a long time, but it will happen: Christianity will go back to its original form. A group will grow that wants to remove added ideas until only what Jesus taught is left. When this change comes to the United States and Europe, people will start to worship like in the time of Jesus, only following his ideas. The church will stay strong to guide them. But as beliefs go back to the past, there will be less diversity in Christian beliefs and practices. Instead of many differences, there will be more similarities. History shows big changes like this. For example, Christians were once hurt by the Roman Empire, but later, the empire became Christian. Our country once had African-American slavery, but now has African-American leaders. The future change will happen in Christianity, going back to the source and reducing diversity. This will happen by understanding Jesus' words in a new way, not just as they were said. So, what happened since Jesus lived? If we look far back, we find only Judaism, which was the start of Christianity. Belief in one God, a religion given by God, and the Hebrew scriptures were central by the time Romans took Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish people were not united. They were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and most were common people.

I believe The Jungle shows that people are naturally greedy and self-centered. They only care about themselves and want to make their lives better. They do not care about those below them. The book shows this in many ways. One clear example is the owners and managers of the big factories. They only want to make their companies as big and great as possible. They do not care who gets hurt or what gets in their way. Upton Sinclair writes, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair shows the damage from pollution. The owners do not care about people or animals getting hurt. They do not care about the smoke or waste from the factories.  

The owners and managers also do not care about their workers. They want to make or save more money. Sinclair writes, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They make their workers work long hours and then might fire many people at once with no warning. There were few or no laws protecting workers at that time. This let managers and owners push workers to go faster and work in bad conditions. The book shows that people in Packingtown had to deal with bad working and living conditions. There were no groups to help workers. Unions existed but often hurt more than helped because they took money from poor workers. The workers were treated so badly they were like slaves. Sinclair writes, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

"Dream-Land" is one of Edgar Allan Poe's favorite poems. In this poem, Poe uses the word "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56. Mabbott says this comes from Virgil. Virgil used "Thulé" to talk about an island north of Britain. The Greeks thought this island was the edge of the world. Virgil did use the word, but there may be another source. Poe liked German writers. This is important because it shows that Poe knew Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," says Poe was copying Goethe. The "Oxford Companion to English Literature" says that Goethe was a famous writer. He wrote the poetic drama "Faust," first published in 1808 and the second part in 1832, the year Goethe died. In the second part of "Faust," there is a poem called "The King of Thulé." This poem is about a king whose wife dies. She gives him a goblet. After she dies, the king drinks a lot and cries. He decides to die, gives his things to his children, but keeps the goblet. He goes to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The king's story is like Poe’s poem "Dream-Land." It shows Poe’s feelings of loss and drinking. "Faust" was made into a drama by H. P. Grattan in 1842, just before Poe used "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum." 

Poe mentions Thule two times in his work. He says "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and uses it twice in "Dream-Land." "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be read together. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about Thule. It is dark and lonely. He sees ghosts of dead friends and a world without color. These scenes are like "The King of Thulé." The king feels lonely after his wife dies and has no will to live or rule. The poem is like the speaker has stepped into Goethe’s poem. Goethe was an important writer. Poe knew about him, partly because he respected Tennyson. Poe said he admired Tennyson. Poe would have known Goethe’s work from many copies made after it was first published.

Under California law, can a customer who was hurt after slipping on an applesauce spill in a store get extra money because the store manager did not clean it up even though he was told twice? The manager was having dinner and did not clean it for thirty minutes. A judge might not quickly throw out Jennifer Palmer's request for extra money. To get extra money, a person must show that the other person acted in a harmful way on purpose and that the action was really bad. Palmer can say that Martin should have known that not cleaning a spill could hurt someone because other people had been hurt by slips in the months before. Even though he knew this, he did not clean the spill. Palmer's claim that Martin's actions were bad is not very strong, but it makes sense because six slip-and-fall incidents happened in 2009, and Martin did not keep his store safe.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, a worker at D&D Markets, told his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill. Martin said he was on a dinner break and did not have time to deal with it. At 5:15 pm, another worker, Mary J. Haddigan, also told Mr. Martin about the spill, and he said the same thing. At 5:30 pm that day, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and hurt her back badly. Before Palmer's accident, there had been five other slips at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is suing D&D for money for her injury, and we are looking at whether to try to stop her claim for extra money.

In California, a person can get extra money if the other person acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." The law says malice is when someone meant to cause harm, or if they did not mean it, their action was very bad and they ignored the safety of others. Courts say conduct is malicious when the person knew their actions could be dangerous but still did not stop. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She always felt like she needed something. It was a desire that could not be filled. It started when she was about 14, just becoming a teenager. It was still there at 17. By then, she decided she wanted a person, not a thing. But she had no interest in boys. Some boys liked her and tried to win her over, but no one interested her. She often asked herself why this happened. She thought about it for years, but found no good answer. So she lived, always asking about her desires.

A day at home was usually calm. Her parents were good and peaceful. They did not fight with each other or with her. They only argued when she wanted to be independent. She was the lively daughter of a calm couple. She was fun and nice, and people liked her.

But today was not calm. As she moved from room to room, looking for new ideas, she heard a scream from the kitchen. It was her mother's voice. She ran in, worried. "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother was on the floor, in pain, saying "Ow" again and again. Her daughter ran to her and tried to help. "Ouch ... sweetie, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." Her mother spoke fast and with pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where to pick you up." Her mother showed her with her hands. The daughter was glad she was strong. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back, and drove.

At the hospital, there were smells of cleaning and sickness, mixed with fear. But she did not notice. Her mind was on helping her mother. She carried her mother in and called for help. Worried faces came, and someone brought a bed with wheels. They put her mother on it and took her away. Her daughter sat and worried.

Her mother had fallen off a stool while trying to get a vase from a high cabinet.

This study wanted to show that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) can lower the risk of heart disease and stroke. A high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score" means you eat this way. The aMed diet is like the Med diet but with more plant foods and fish. It has less meat and bad fats. Some alcohol is okay.

Earlier studies showed that the Med diet can help you live longer and lose weight better than a low-fat diet. But they did not look at stroke risk.

This study followed 74,886 women, ages 38 to 63, who did not have heart disease or diabetes. They were part of the Nurses' Health Study. From 1984 to 2004, six times, the authors used "food frequency questionnaires" ("FFQs) to find out how much the women followed the aMed diet. Over 95% of the women stayed in the study for 20 years. The FFQs were checked to make sure they were accurate. Reports of heart disease, fatal heart disease, and stroke were confirmed by medical records. If records were not there, some cases were called “probable.”

They also looked at body weight, smoking, aspirin use, vitamin intake, and menopause. Starting in 1986, they checked physical activity. To get a better idea of long-term diet, they averaged the aMed scores over time. They adjusted for things that could change the results, like age, smoking, and physical activity.

They used a special model to see how the aMed score related to heart disease and stroke risk. They looked at fatal and nonfatal cases separately.

Women who followed the Med diet more closely had lower risk of heart disease and stroke. In 20 years, there were 2391 new cases of heart disease, 1763 new cases of stroke, and 1077 deaths from heart disease and stroke. Women with the highest aMed scores had a lower risk (relative risk [RR], 0.71) than those with the lowest scores.

The sign says Hitler is alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner. She holds a piece of cardboard over her head. The sign has an unsettling message written with a pen. Burma, also called Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. It is ruled by a military group that took power in 1962. In 2007, many street protests took place. These were the first public protests in ten years. Many monks led these protests. The protests were called "The Saffron Revolution" because of the color of the monks' robes. At first, the public began to join the protests, and the government allowed it. But soon, the situation became violent. It was like a war between the monks and the military. The military attacked monasteries. Foreign journalists were arrested. A Japanese journalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27th, 2007, for being at a protest. The official report said 13 people died. But Colonel Hla Win, who left the army before the report, said many more people died, maybe thousands.

This is not new. Governments have always tried to stop dissent. They want complete control over their people. Long ago, Roman emperors said they were chosen by gods to rule. Japanese emperors were seen as gods, sent to lead their people. President George W. Bush has calls with Ted Haggard, leader of a group called Stupid People Worldwide, linked to the Republic Party.

Some well-known examples of such actions are the 1989 protest at Tiananmen Square. People gathered to protest the government. The death toll is unclear, with the Chinese government saying 200-300 died, but the Chinese Red Cross said 2,000-3,000 died. Another example is the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s. Hutu groups, helped by the government, killed Tutsis and political moderates. Hitler’s 'Third Reich' is another example, where many Jewish people were killed over several years in many countries.

Duke Ellington is important in jazz for many reasons. He lived a long life and was very creative with his orchestra. In many of his songs, you can hear Ellington playing the piano, but it is often in a quiet way. As a composer, Ellington was great at making rich and complex songs. These songs showed off the talents of the people in his band. He created a space where a soloist could play freely. He also wrote music that was well-planned and used the special style of each band member to show musical ideas. This helped to create a unique sound for the orchestra. Ellington was a master at knowing how each player sounded and how they all fit together. This helped him write some of the most new and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's sound and new ideas. It mentions "Creole Love Call" as an early example of using voice as a jazz instrument without words. This piece shows Ellington's skill in matching the style of his soloists. The song is a slow, twelve-bar blues with six parts:

1. The first part is a call and response between voice and reeds. The voice starts smooth and melodic, then gets rougher at the end.
2. The second part is a muted trumpet solo that adds to the main tune and uses blue notes.
3. The third part is a clarinet solo played high, with a soft piano in the background.
4. The fourth part is the full band echoing the first part with a call and response between brass and reeds.
5. The fifth part is exciting, with high reeds and a syncopated stop-time from brass and rhythm.
6. The sixth part goes back to the start with call and response between voice and reeds. Here, the voice uses a "growl" technique like an instrument.

A short end part has a vocal run and a strange trombone finish. Ellington's use of voice adds a layer of tone color to his work.

In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington mixes tight orchestration with tone color. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing creates a rich sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" builds on these ideas. Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a key player in his band, to introduce the melody on muted trombone.

Why do living things change in the way they do? Are there limits that affect how they change over time? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that scientists do not yet know how to describe even simple living shapes with math. This is still true today. But now, people use math to study how mollusk shells grow and change over time. Our study looks at how math and experiments can help us understand changes in Prunum shells. We used X-ray images of Prunum to find measurements for modeling shell shapes. We used these numbers in a program called CerioShell. We created different shell shapes to see how Prunum shells might change. We are combining these results with other studies to learn about big changes in Prunum over time.

A shell is like a tube that turns in a circle. These turns are called whorls, and they spiral around an imaginary line called the axis. The axis goes through the middle of the shell, called the columella. Whorls grow at different speeds, and a line called a suture divides them. The biggest whorl is the last one, called the body whorl. All other whorls make up the spire. The top of the spire is the apex, and the bottom is the base. The animal comes out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be looked at from different views: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The usual way to look at a shell is from the apertural view, with the aperture facing you and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first look at the shell from the top view. Find where the first suture starts. Draw a line to split the shell into two parts. Count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell grows as the animal builds it over time. You can follow the path of the aperture by noting the center of each whorl’s aperture and its size. This path can be shown in pictures and math. Once you have a math formula, you can change how the mollusk’s shell grows.

The rate of deaths among newborn babies and infants in Indonesia has not changed much in the last ten years. The country is doing well in reaching some goals, like water and sanitation. But it is not doing well in improving health for children and mothers. It needs more improvement to reach the goals by 2015. We will talk about the reasons below. It shows that the health system needs to be stronger, not just focus on specific programs.

Indonesia has made progress with more births attended by skilled health workers. Now, 72% of births meet this goal. But this number includes traditional workers, like midwives, who cannot help if there are serious problems during birth. This means many mothers die from heavy bleeding. So, this progress is not as good as it seems, and more work is needed. Also, fewer children under five with diarrhea are treated by health professionals. We do not have complete data on care after birth, but it is still a problem in the country.

The rate of cesarean sections is low, about 4%. This is another problem. The rate is 7% in cities, but only 2% in rural areas. This shows that healthcare services are mostly in urban areas. There is also a problem of access for poor people. There is a 27% difference in service use between the poorest and richest groups. Poor people have a hard time getting healthcare, likely because of high costs.

To improve care for newborns and mothers, we need to know how to fix the lack of service. Should Indonesia create specific programs or make the whole health system better without just focusing on care before and after pregnancy? Specific programs are appealing because they have clear goals and can show results faster. But there are problems too. Focusing on one area can take away resources from other areas. It can also lead to too many separate programs that do not work well together. This increases paperwork and makes it harder to get supplies and funding.

In the past 100 years, Popular Music has grown to include many kinds. It is hard to name all of them. Rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk are just a few. Each kind has smaller groups inside it. Heavy Metal rock has become very different and expressive in the past 40 years. It shows many feelings, often darker ones. It is different because people saw it could change and made new kinds from it. This led to even more new kinds, and it still grows today.

Now, Heavy Metal is so varied that it is hard to say what it really is. It has many ideas from other music kinds. To understand metal music today, we need to know what the metal movement is and why it is a movement, not just a kind of music.

Metal is a movement often linked with darkness. It can be called "music of more"—more bass, more sound, more violence, more show. People in metal bands are good at playing their instruments, and it shows in the music. Metal is also a movement with a lot of drug use. In the mid-70s, a lot of people used psychedelic drugs. This led to wild and strange music. The drugs were a reason for making such music. Metal has many dark and deep qualities. This was new because much popular music was not dark. Later metal took ideas from the Romantic Era, which was also dark. Lyrics from songs like Helter Skelter show this darkness.

Helter Skelter is a song that shows the darker side of the Beatles. It goes up and down, like a drug experience. Some say it is one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a reply to a Rolling Stones song, which was also dark. The Beatles wanted to show they could be just as heavy as the Stones, so they included it on The White Album.

Many years before Surrealist artists painted dreamlike pictures, Henri Rousseau made his own dream pictures. He did this both in his mind and on canvas. The Dream is a painting from 1910 by the well-known artist Rousseau. It shows a woman amazed by the land she sees in a dream. It also shows Rousseau’s dreams and goals as a painter. He wanted to be known, liked, and praised by other artists and people who love art. But he had a hard choice to make. Should he paint like others to be accepted by the art world he loved, or should he paint in his own way and be different?

To understand The Dream this way, we need to know a bit about Rousseau’s life. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France. His father worked with metal and sold hardware. As a child, Rousseau did not learn art in school. He worked until he was forty for the French toll service. People wrongly called him a customs inspector. His first wife, Clémence, died after they lost eight babies. He only had one child left, a daughter named Julia. This made him very sad. Rousseau wanted a new start and found comfort in painting. Unlike other artists of his time who painted peasants in a romantic way, Rousseau was a folk painter. He had the dreams of an average person of his class.

Rousseau wanted the art world to accept him. This makes sense when we think about his life. He did not learn art in school and started painting later in life. He also made art at the same time as many famous artists. Even after many years of work, Rousseau did not get much attention until artists like Matisse became known. In the book Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon says that Rousseau and Matisse were different. They were not just different in style and subjects, but also in why they painted. Matisse was afraid of making boring art, while Rousseau wanted to make traditional art to join the Artiste Français.

Many great thinkers have thought about the link between ethics and beauty, and truth and beauty. I think there is a reason for this. In “Ode on a Grecian Urn,” John Keats says, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty - That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” We learn much in life through school or experience. But we seem to understand ethics and beauty, as Keats suggests, without being taught. Ethics and beauty try to describe rather than give rules. We study why art or writing is beautiful, or why an action is moral, not to set rules for making good art or moral acts.

Criticism of art or morals cannot fully explain what is good or beautiful. Talking about da Vinci's Mona Lisa may include ideas like foreground, background, and contrast. But in the end, these do not explain why it is good art. Often, when asked about a favorite piece of art or writing, people say, “There's just something about it” before giving a complex explanation. Both art and morals cannot be fully described by their features.
